    <h1>DPT_CannonBarrelHeat</h1>
    <div class="subtitle">Component Reference Guide<br>
    <span style="font-size: 11pt; font-style: normal;">A lightweight, event-driven utility designed to manage the emissive cooldown of weapon barrels over time, entirely decoupling visual heat decay from strict Animator clip durations.</span></div>

    <h2>1. Inspector Property Configuration</h2>
    
    <h3>Dependencies & Heat Settings</h3>
    <p>Configures the baseline emission strength and the rate at which the material returns to its resting state.</p>
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th style="width: 30%;">Property</th>
                <th>Description</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Shader Variation</strong></td>
                <td>The scene reference to the <code>DPT_ShaderVariation</code> component managing the barrel's material. The script pushes calculated alpha values directly to this target to control emission intensity.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Cooling Duration</strong></td>
                <td>The time (in seconds) it takes for the barrel to cool down from its maximum heat back to a dark (zero alpha) state.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Max Heat Alpha</strong></td>
                <td>The peak emission strength applied to the material the exact moment the weapon is fired. Values above 1.0 will push the shader into HDR ranges for intense bloom effects.</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>2. Technical Architecture</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Animator Decoupling:</strong> Because weapon firing animations are often extremely short, tying emission directly to an animation curve forces the glow to end prematurely. This script intercepts a single trigger and handles the mathematical decay smoothly over time, spanning seamlessly across idle or reload states.</li>
        <li><strong>Event-Driven Trigger:</strong> The script sits entirely dormant with zero <code>Update</code> overhead until the public <code>FireCannonHeat()</code> method is called. This is designed to be triggered via an <strong>Animation Event</strong> on the exact frame the projectile leaves the barrel, or directly via your C# weapon firing logic.</li>
        <li><strong>Cross-Assembly Integration:</strong> Operates natively with the <code>DPT.Core</code> assembly. By modifying the <code>InstanceColor.a</code> property of the variation script, it pushes variables straight to the optimized GPU instancing stream without breaking batching or allocating new material instances.</li>
    </ul>

